This week, the shortlist for the hypothetical 1894 Booker Prize consists of six classic and  bestseller books, which stirred the fin de siecle world and remain compelling today.
The  retrospective raises questions about how the relationship between literature and society has  changed in the past 100 years.
Victorians were lovers of contemporary fiction.
Middle class writers and readers were more  homogenous and more certain of their place in the mainstream.
The novel was their political and  intellectual forum.
Modernism weakened 20th century belief in the novel and the dominance of  film and television has made novels a more marginal form. 
